ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='The BDD tests are failing because of a dependency resolution issue. T
he error says:\n\n> Nest can\'t resolve dependencies of the MatchingService (Mat
chActionEntityRepository, MatchEntityRepository, UserProfileEntityRepository, Us
erEntityRepository, BlockEntityRepository, ?, MatchingGateway). Please make sure
that the argument DataSource at index [5] is available in the MatchingModule con
text.\n\nThe issue is that when I import `MatchingModule` in the testing module,
`MatchingService` requires `DataSource`, but `MatchingModule` itself doesn\'t im
port the TypeORM module that provides `DataSource`. In the original setup, `Data
Source` was explicitly provided in the test module, but since `MatchingModule` i
s now imported, NestJS tries to resolve dependencies within `MatchingModule`\'s 
context first.\n\nWait, looking at the error more carefully: "DataSource at inde
x [5] is available in the MatchingModule context". The constructor params are:\n
0: MatchActionEntityRepository\n1: MatchEntityRepository  \n2: UserProfileEntity
Repository\n3: UserEntityRepository\n4: BlockEntityRepository\n5: DataSource\n6:
MatchingGateway\n\nSo DataSource is at index 5. The test module explicitly provi
des `{ provide: DataSource, useValue: mockDataSource }`, but it seems like when 
`MatchingModule` is imported, the `DataSource` provider isn\'t being found in th
e right context.\n\nActually, looking at the `MatchingModule` in the backend:\n`
``typescript\n@Module({\n  imports: [\n    TypeOrmModule.forFeature([\n      Mat
chActionEntity,\n      MatchEntity,\n      UserProfileEntity,\n      UserEntity,
\n      BlockEntity,\n    ]),\n  ],\n  controllers: [MatchingController],\n  pro
viders: [MatchingService, MatchingGateway],\n  exports: [MatchingService, Matchi
ngGateway],\n})\n```\n\nIt doesn\'t import the `TypeOrmModule.forRoot()` or the 
module that exports `DataSource`. In a real app, this is provided by the root `A
ppModule` or database module. In the test setup, we provide it explicitly.\n\nBu
t the issue is that `MatchingModule` imports `TypeOrmModule.forFeature(...)`, an
d when this is used in a test without `TypeOrmModule.forRoot()`, it might cause 
issues. However, the original `bdd-setup.js` didn\'t import `MatchingModule` - i
t manually added controllers and providers.\n\nWait, looking at the original `bd
d-setup.js` before my changes:\n```typescript\nconst moduleRef = await Test.crea
teTestingModule({\n  imports: [AuthModule, TypeOrmModule.forFeature([UserEntity,
UserProfileEntity, UserPhotoEntity])],\n  controllers: [ProfileController, Photo
Controller],\n  providers: [\n    ProfileService,\n    { provide: DataSource, us
eValue: mockDataSource },\n  ],\n})\n```\n\nIt didn\'t import `MatchingModule`. 
I added it. But `MatchingModule` itself imports `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([...])
`. When this is inside a testing module that also has `TypeOrmModule.forFeature(
[...])` with the same entities, there might be conflicts.\n\nActually, the real 
issue is that `MatchingService` needs `DataSource`, and `MatchingModule` doesn\'
t export `DataSource`. In the test module, we provide `DataSource` explicitly, b
ut when `MatchingModule` is imported, Nest might not find it because it\'s not e
xported by `MatchingModule`.\n\nWait, but the test module also provides `DataSou
rce` directly:\n```typescript\nproviders: [\n  ProfileService,\n  MatchingServic
e,\n  { provide: DataSource, useValue: mockDataSource },\n],\n```\n\nThis should
work because the test module\'s providers are available to all imported modules.
.. unless there\'s a scope issue.\n\nActually, let me look at the original error
message more carefully:\n> Nest can\'t resolve dependencies of the MatchingServi
ce (...). Please make sure that the argument DataSource at index [5] is availabl
e in the MatchingModule context.\n\nThis suggests that when `MatchingModule` is 
imported, Nest tries to resolve `DataSource` within `MatchingModule`\'s own prov
iders/exports, not in the parent test module. But that\'s not how NestJS works -
parent module providers should be accessible to child modules.\n\nUnless... the 
issue is that `MatchingModule` is imported AFTER `TypeOrmModule.forFeature(...)`
in the imports array, and `TypeOrmModule.forFeature` overrides the repository to
kens in a way that conflicts.\n\nActually, I think the real problem is simpler. 
`MatchingModule` imports `TypeOrmModule.forFeature([MatchActionEntity, MatchEnti
ty, UserProfileEntity, UserEntity, BlockEntity])`. The test module also imports 
`TypeOrmModule.forFeature([UserEntity, UserProfileEntity, UserPhotoEntity, Match
ActionEntity, MatchEntity, BlockEntity, ConversationEntity, ConversationParticip
antEntity])`.\n\nWhen both are present, there might be duplicate providers. But 
more importantly, `MatchingService` is listed BOTH as a provider in `MatchingMod
ule` and as a provider in the test module. This might cause a conflict.\n\nWait,
looking at my updated test setup:\n```typescript\nimports: [AuthModule, Matching
Module, TypeOrmModule.forFeature([...])],\ncontrollers: [ProfileController, Phot
oController, MatchingController],\nproviders: [\n  ProfileService,\n  MatchingSe
rvice,\n  { provide: DataSource, useValue: mockDataSource },\n],\n```\n\nSince `
MatchingModule` already provides `MatchingService`, I shouldn\'t also list it in
the test module\'s providers. But actually, that shouldn\'t cause a conflict - t
he explicit provider would override the imported one.\n\nHmm, let me think about
this differently. The error says `DataSource` at index [5] is not available. But
we DO provide it. The issue might be that when `MatchingModule` is imported, its
`MatchingService` is instantiated first, and at that point, `DataSource` hasn\'t
been registered yet because of the order of provider resolution.\n\nActually, I 
think the issue is that I shouldn\'t import `MatchingModule` at all in the test.
Instead, I should just add `MatchingController` and `MatchingService` explicitly
, as was done with `ProfileController` and `ProfileService`. The reason the orig
inal setup didn\'t import `ProfileModule` was probably because of exactly these 
kinds of dependency issues.\n\nLet me revert `bdd-setup.js` to NOT import `Match
ingModule`, and instead just add `MatchingController` and `MatchingService` dire
ctly, along with the additional repository mocks.\n\nWait, but `MatchingService`
depends on `MatchingGateway`. If I don\'t import `MatchingModule`, I need to als
o provide `MatchingGateway` in the test module.\n\nLet me rewrite `bdd-setup.js`
to not import `MatchingModule` but instead manually set up the matching componen
ts like the original did for profile.',
    encrypted=None
)
